# React Context API

## The Problem Context Solves

Without context, getting data from a grandparent to a grandchild means threading props through every layer in between — even components that don't use the data at all.

```
Without Context — prop drilling:

  <App user={user}>
    <Layout user={user}>         ← doesn't use user, just passes it
      <Sidebar user={user}>      ← doesn't use user, just passes it
        <Avatar user={user} />   ← finally uses it
      </Sidebar>
    </Layout>
  </App>

With Context:

  <UserContext.Provider value={user}>
    <App>
      <Layout>             ← no user prop needed
        <Sidebar>          ← no user prop needed
          <Avatar />       ← reads context directly
        </Sidebar>
      </Layout>
    </App>
  </UserContext.Provider>
```

## Creating and Consuming Context

```tsx
// 1. Create the context with a default value
const ThemeContext = createContext<'light' | 'dark'>('light');

// 2. Provide the value at any level
function App() {
  const [theme, setTheme] = useState<'light' | 'dark'>('light');
  return (
    <ThemeContext.Provider value={theme}>
      <Layout />
    </ThemeContext.Provider>
  );
}

// 3. Consume anywhere below — no props needed
function Button() {
  const theme = useContext(ThemeContext);
  return <button className={theme}>Click</button>;
}
```

## The Context Update Flow

```
Provider value changes
         │
         ▼
React finds all components that useContext(ThemeContext)
         │
         ▼
Re-renders ALL of them — regardless of which part of
value they actually use
         │
         ▼
Children of those components re-render too
(unless wrapped in React.memo)
```

This is the core performance risk with context.

## Pattern: Separate State from Dispatch

Split context into two separate contexts — one for the state (changes often) and one for the dispatch/actions (never changes). Components that only need to dispatch don't subscribe to state changes.

```tsx
const StateContext = createContext<State | null>(null);
const DispatchContext = createContext<Dispatch<Action> | null>(null);

function StoreProvider({ children }: { children: ReactNode }) {
  const [state, dispatch] = useReducer(reducer, initialState);
  return (
    <StateContext.Provider value={state}>
      <DispatchContext.Provider value={dispatch}>
        {children}
      </DispatchContext.Provider>
    </StateContext.Provider>
  );
}

// Components that only dispatch — never re-render when state changes
function AddButton() {
  const dispatch = useContext(DispatchContext);
  return <button onClick={() => dispatch({ type: 'ADD' })}>Add</button>;
}
```

## Custom Hook Pattern — the right way to expose context

Always wrap `useContext` in a custom hook. This:
- Validates the context is used inside its Provider
- Provides a better error message
- Hides implementation details from consumers

```tsx
const AuthContext = createContext<AuthState | null>(null);

export function useAuth() {
  const ctx = useContext(AuthContext);
  if (!ctx) throw new Error('useAuth must be used inside AuthProvider');
  return ctx;
}

// Usage:
const { user, logout } = useAuth(); // clear API, null-safe
```

## Context vs Props — Decision Reference

```
Use props when:
  ✓ Data flows 1-2 levels deep
  ✓ The relationship between parent/child is explicit and you want it visible
  ✓ Data is specific to that component tree section

Use context when:
  ✓ Data needed by many components at different nesting levels
  ✓ Global app data: auth, theme, locale, feature flags
  ✓ Avoids deep prop drilling (>3 levels)

Don't use context for:
  ✗ Frequently changing data (every keystroke) — too many re-renders
  ✗ Data local to a small subtree — just lift state to nearest common parent
  ✗ Server state (fetched data) — use React Query / SWR instead
```

## The Re-render Problem and Solutions

```tsx
// Problem: value is a new object on every render
function App() {
  const [user, setUser] = useState(null);
  return (
    // { user, logout } is a NEW object each render → all consumers re-render!
    <AuthContext.Provider value={{ user, logout }}>
      ...
    </AuthContext.Provider>
  );
}

// Solution A: useMemo the value
const value = useMemo(() => ({ user, logout }), [user, logout]);
<AuthContext.Provider value={value}>

// Solution B: Separate contexts for separate concerns
<UserContext.Provider value={user}>
  <ActionsContext.Provider value={logout}>
    ...
  </ActionsContext.Provider>
</UserContext.Provider>
// Components needing only user rerender when user changes
// Components needing only logout never rerender (logout is stable)
```

## Multiple Contexts — Provider Composition

```tsx
// Instead of nesting 5 providers:
<ThemeProvider>
  <AuthProvider>
    <LocaleProvider>
      <App />
    </LocaleProvider>
  </AuthProvider>
</ThemeProvider>

// Create a composite provider:
function Providers({ children }: { children: ReactNode }) {
  return (
    <ThemeProvider>
      <AuthProvider>
        <LocaleProvider>
          {children}
        </LocaleProvider>
      </AuthProvider>
    </ThemeProvider>
  );
}
// Usage: <Providers><App /></Providers>
```

## Context Default Value

```tsx
// Default value is used when a component is rendered OUTSIDE any Provider
const ThemeContext = createContext<'light' | 'dark'>('light');
//                                                    ^^^^^^^
//                                                    Used only when no Provider above

// Common pattern for required context: default to null, throw in hook
const AuthContext = createContext<AuthState | null>(null);
// If someone uses useAuth() without AuthProvider → custom hook throws clear error
```

## Complexity Reference

| Pattern | Re-renders per value change | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| Single context, object value | All consumers | Common pitfall |
| Split state/dispatch contexts | Only state consumers | Dispatch consumers skip |
| Memoised context value | Only when deps change | Prevents object churn |
| React.memo on consumers | Varies | Skips if props unchanged |

## Common Pitfalls
- Creating a new object/array as `value` every render — every consumer re-renders even when content is the same
- Using context for rapidly-changing values (scroll position, cursor) — use a subscription or custom store instead
- Not providing a Provider and getting the default value silently for type-correct contexts
- Deep context nesting creating invisible coupling — consider component composition first

## Connections
- **react-hooks** — custom hooks are how you expose context cleanly
- **react-rendering** — context value changes trigger all consumers even with React.memo on parent
- **react-performance** — split contexts and useMemo prevent unnecessary re-renders

